“The sea is ours”: Bolivia, blocked, hopes that the court will reopen the path to the Pacific
Sailors patrol on an armoured boat in naval headquarters La Paz.
The public buildings carry a blue flag like the ocean.
From Lake Titicaca to the Amazon, the naval bases display the following motorcycle: "The sea is right to us.
Recovering it is a duty.”
Throughout blocked Bolivia, the memory of a coast lost for the benefit of Chile during a bloody resource conflict in the 19th century is still well present, just as the desire to navigate the Pacific Ocean, once again.
These hopes have not been so palpable for several decades; Bolivia is indeed awaiting a decision of the International Court of Justice, which will be rendered on 1 October, after five years of deliberations.
“Bolivia has will, a spirit of unity and serenity, and of course expects a positive outcome,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will follow the decision of the International Court of Justice on a large screen across the country, hoping that the Hague court will rule in favour of the Bolivian request. Bolivia hopes that, after decades of sporadic negotiations, Chile will be required to negotiate the agreement on a sovereign ocean transition to Bolivia.
Evo Morales, the charismatic indigenous president of Bolivia (who faces a controversial fight for re-election next year), also has a lot to say about the decision to be made on Monday.
“We are so close to being able to return to the Pacific Ocean,” he said at the end of August.
But some analysts believe that the court is unlikely to rule in favor of Chile, and that few things would change, even in the event of a positive decision.
The United Nations body based in the Netherlands has no power to grant Chilean territory, and has stipulated that it will not determine the outcome of the possible talks.
The fact that the International Court of Justice issues its decision six months after the latest arguments shows that the case “was not complicated,” says Paz Zárate, a Chilean international law expert.
And far from promoting the cause of Bolivia, the last four years may even have harmed it.
“The problem of access to the sea has been diverted by the current Bolivian administration,” Zárate said.
Morales’ warlike rhetoric undermined all the Chilean goodwill that remained, she suggested.
Bolivia and Chile will continue to exchange, but after that, it will be very difficult to organize talks.
The last exchange of ambassadors between the two countries took place in 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, who represents Bolivia in The Hague, rejected the idea that the Court's decision was abnormally quick.
Monday will bring Bolivia “an extraordinary opportunity to start a new era of relations with Chile” and a chance to “end 139 years of disagreements with mutual benefits,” he said.
Calzadilla also disputed the fact that Morales - who remains one of Latin America's most popular presidents to date - used the maritime problem as a political bend.
