John Edward: Language skills are essential for citizens of the world
Independent schools in Scotland maintain a record of school excellence, which continued in 2018 with excellent new exam results reinforced by collective and individual success in sports, art, music and other community activities.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) strive to provide the best level of service to students and their parents.
Independent schools work to prepare their students for higher education, the career they have chosen and their place as citizens of the world.
As an education sector capable of designing and implementing a tailor-made school curriculum, we see that contemporary languages remain popular and desired subjects in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, you speak to his head.
If you speak to him in his tongue, you speak to his heart.”
This reminds us that we cannot rely on English to build relationships and establish a trustworthy link with people from other countries.
Looking at the excellent results at the exams this year, we find that languages are at the top of the ranking, with the highest success rates in independent schools.
In total, 68% of students who studied foreign languages earned the highest rating, A.
Data, collected from the 74 SCIS member schools, show that 72% of students received the highest grade, A, in Mandarin, as well as 72% of students who studied German, 69% of students who studied French and 63% of students who studied Spanish.
This shows that Scotland's independent schools support foreign languages as absolutely essential skills for children and youth in the future.
Now languages as subjects are organized as well as science, technology, engineering and mathematics in the programs of independent schools and other schools.
A survey by the UK Employment and Skills Commission conducted in 2014 shows that among the difficulties that employers face in recruiting candidates, 17% are linked to insufficient language skills.
Language skills are therefore becoming more and more vital in preparing young people for their future careers.
With more job offers requiring languages, these skills are essential in our globalized world.
Regardless of their career choice, a person who speaks a second language will benefit from a real advantage in the future thanks to this lasting skill.
Being able to communicate directly with foreigners will automatically place the multilingual person in front of its competitors.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of 4,000 adults living in the UK, 75% of them lacked sufficient control of a foreign language to hold a conversation. French was the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage (15%).
This is why investing in language learning is important for children today.
By speaking several languages, including those of emerging economies, children will have a better chance of finding a rewarding job.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Many of them will focus on contemporary classical languages, while others will teach languages considered important for the UK in the 2020 perspective, including Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child’s preferences, several languages will be accessible in independent schools, with specialist staff in the field.
Scottish independent schools want to provide a learning environment that will prepare children and give them the skills they need to succeed, regardless of what the future reserves for them.
It is obvious that languages remain of vital importance to the future of the country at present, in a global trade environment, and this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should be regarded as “international communication skills.”
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to Scottish youth.
We have to do it.
John Edward is the director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
