While reiterating North Korea's well-known accusations of Washington's opposition to a "step-by-step" approach to denuclearization under which North Korea would be rewarded if it was gradually taking action, its statement proved important in that it did not reject the idea of unilateral denuclearization like Pyongyang.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump, made on June 12 in Singapore at the first summit between a current U.S. president and a North Korean leader, when Kim pledged to work in favor of a “denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula” while Trump promised to guarantee North Korea’s security.
North Korea seeks to officially end the Korean War (1950-1953), but the United States has stated that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington also refused requests to ease severe international sanctions against North Korea.
The U.S. insists that North Korea first proceed to denuclearization and increases pressure by imposing sanctions to achieve their goal in a coercive manner, opposing even "the declaration of end of war".
“Those who think these sanctions can make us do not know us.
The problem is that maintaining sanctions increases our distrust.”
Nothing has commented on the U.S. leader’s second summit between Kim and Trump highlighted before the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister stressed three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If the side concerned with the denuclearization issue were South Korea and not the United States, denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not be in such a stalemate.”
Nevertheless, the tone of Ri’s speech was radically different from last year’s when he declared before the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable to point North Korean missiles on North American territory after the “evil” President Trump called Kim a “missile man” on a suicide mission.
Trump, who threatened before the UN last year to “completely destroy” North Korea, did not praise this year for the courage with which Kim applied disarmament measures, but added that there is still much to be done and that sanctions will not be lifted until North Korea disarms.
