Harvard: Students Take Rest Classes
This year, Harvard University has set up a new course that allows all undergraduate students to sleep more and fight the growing machist tendency to study by consuming caffeine all night.
A professor has noticed that most students from the world’s best university don’t know how to take care of them.
This course, designed by Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, is according to him the first of its kind in the United States.
It was after giving a lecture on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning that the idea came to him.
At the end, a student approached and asked me, “Why are you telling me that only in the last year?”
She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
This course, given for the first time this year, explains to students the need to adopt good sleep patterns to improve their academic and physical performance, as well as their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and director general of the university’s health services, said the university had decided to introduce the course after finding that students suffered from severe lack of sleep during the week.
The class time consists of different interactive exercises.
One of the sections presents the image of a dormitory containing different objects (coffee cups, curtains, sneakers, books...) on which students click to know the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of lack of sleep on their physical performance and the importance of integrating a routine before bed.
In another section, participants learn how long-term lack of sleep can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons then invites participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know that this will not instantly change the behaviour of students.
However, in our opinion, they have the right to know this information - in the same way that you have the right to know what the health effects of smoking are," said Professor Czeisler.
According to him, the culture of pride in “spending a white night” still exists, and he adds that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students make lack of sleep a growing problem.
Having enough and good quality sleep should be students’ “secret weapon” to fight stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said – even to avoid gaining weight, because lack of sleep puts the brain in hunger mode, making them hungry permanently.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian student of chemistry and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design this course after being one of his students last year, during his first year at Harvard.
He claimed that this course had opened his eyes and prompted him to insist that it be offered throughout the campus.
He hopes that the next step will be to offer all postgraduate students to follow a similar curriculum before joining the renowned institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students provide an alarm for both bedtime and wake-uptime, and be aware of the harmful effects of “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LED light, which can disrupt their circadian rhythm and cause sleep disorders.
