Almanach: The inventor of the Geiger meter
And now, a page of our "Sunday Morning" Almanach: On September 30, 1882, 136 years ago today, and THE TOURNE COUNTER... was born the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger, in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity; an invention that subsequently gave birth to the device known as the Geiger meter.
Pillar of science since then, the Geiger counter has also become fundamental in pop culture, as can be seen in the 1950 film "Bells of Coronado", with Roy Rogers and Dale Evans, two unlikely scientists:
A man: “What is this?”
Rogers: “It’s a Geiger meter, we use it to look for radioactive minerals, such as uranium.
“Thanks to these headphones, we can actually hear the effects of atoms released in minerals by radioactivity.”
Evans: “Tell me, I’m sure it’s going to jump out there!”
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945, a few days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears its name remains.
