Germany's new warship delayed
According to local media, the new German Navy fregate should have been put into service in 2014 to replace ageing warships dating from the Cold War, but it will not be in service until at least next year due to faulty systems and exponential expenses.
According to the newspaper Die Zeit, which quotes a military spokesman, the commissioning of the Rheinland-Pfalz, the flagship of the brand new Baden-Württemberg frigates, was postponed to the first half of 2019.
The ship should have joined the Navy in 2014, but the concerning problems arising after delivery compromised the fate of this ambitious project.
The four ships of the Baden-Württemberg class that the Navy ordered in 2007 will replace the aging fregates of the Bremen class.
It is certain that they will be equipped with a powerful gun, a range of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, as well as some stealing technologies, such as a radar, infrared and reduced acoustic signature.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods - it should be possible to deploy the latest fregates for up to two years outside the attached ports.
According to Die Zeit, however, the continuous delays mean that the avant-garde warships – which should allow Germany to project its overseas force – will already be obsolete when they are put into service.
Last year, the cursed F125 fregat made the headlines when the German Navy officially refused to put the ship into service and sent it back to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This was the first time the Navy returned a ship to a ship manufacturer after its delivery.
The reasons for this return were little known, but the German media mentioned a number of “software and hardware defects” that made the warship unnecessary when deployed on a combat mission.
The software defects were particularly important as the Baden-Württemberg class ships will be operated by a crew of about 120 sailors, which corresponds to half of the crews of the old Bremen class fregates.
In addition, it appears that the ship is significantly overloaded, which decreases its performance and reduces the Navy's ability to make future improvements.
It is estimated that the 7,000-tonne Rheinland-Pfalz weighs twice as heavy as similar-class ships used by the Germans during World War II.
Beyond the failures of the computer system, the cost of the project as a whole - including crew training - also becomes a problem.
