He regretted that none of the fregates of the Baden-Württemberg class could join the Navy.
The National Trust monitors the secret life of bats
New research in a field of the Scottish Highlands seeks to reveal how bats use the landscape in their quest for food.
It is hoped that the observations will shed new light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and guide future conservation activities.
The study by National Trust for Scotland researchers will follow common pipistriles and sopranos as well as long-eared brown bats and Daubenton at Inverewe Garden, Wester Ross.
Special recording devices will be placed at key locations around the property to track bat activities throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile studies using portable detectors.
A professional sound analysis will determine the frequency of bat screams and the activities of the different species.
A map and a habitat report will be prepared to provide a detailed picture of their behaviour across the territory.
Rob Dewar, Nature Conservation Advisor for the NTS, hopes that the results will reveal the most important areas of the habitat for bats and how they are used by each of these species.
This information will identify the benefits of habitat management work such as the creation of meadows and the best way to preserve forests for bats and related species.
In Scotland and the United Kingdom, bat populations have declined considerably over the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development work that affects perch and leads to the loss of their habitat.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, just as flip papers and certain chemical treatments of building materials, as well as cat attacks.
Bats are not really blind.
However, given their night hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique to spot insects and obstacles on their flight route.
Responsible for the protection of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, the NTS takes bats very seriously.
It has ten trained experts, who regularly conduct surveys, inspections on the pier and sometimes rescues.
The organization also established the first and only bat reserve in Scotland at the Threave site in Dumfries and Galloway, which houses eight of Scotland's ten species of bats.
David Thompson, domain manager, says the site is the ideal territory for them.
“Here at Threave we have a great place for bats,” he said.
“We have old buildings, lots of old trees and all the right habitat.
But there is still a lot to learn about bats, so the work we do here and elsewhere will help us better understand what bats need to thrive.”
It emphasizes the importance of checking the presence of bats before proceeding to maintain the properties, because by unwittingly destroying a single maternity nest, one can thus cause the death of 400 females and young, or even the disappearance of an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill them, disturb them, or destroy their perches.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish head of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help.
She said, “We still have a lot to learn about our bats and as far as many of our species are concerned, we don’t know what is happening in their populations at the moment.”
