2004: A major earthquake on 26 December on the west coast of the Indonesian province of Aceh triggered a tsunami that struck 14 countries, causing 226,000 casualties on the coast of the Indian Ocean, more than half of them in Aceh.
2005: Several violent earthquakes shake the west coast of Sumatra from late March to early April.
A few hundred people died on the island of Nias off Sumatra.
2006: A magnitude 6.8 earthquake hit southern Java, the most populated island in Indonesia, triggering a tsunami that hit the southern coast and killed nearly 700 people.
2009: A 7.6-magnitude earthquake struck the city of Padang, the capital of West Sumatra province.
More than 1,100 people were killed.
2010: A 7.5-magnitude earthquake devastated one of the Mentawai Islands off Sumatra and triggered a tsunami of more than 10 meters that destroyed dozens of villages and killed about 300 people.
2016: A superficial earthquake shook the regency of Pidie Jaya in Aceh, causing destruction and panic, reminding residents of the devastation caused by the deadly 2004 earthquake and tsunami.
