Point info on the red tide: Lower concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report by the Florida Fisheries and Wildlife Commission indicates a general decrease in red tide concentrations in certain areas of the Tampa Bay region.
According to the CPF, more irregular flowering conditions are reported in the areas of the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier - which fears declining concentrations.
The red tide covers about 209 km (130 miles) of coastline, from the north of Pinellas to the south of the counties of Lee.
Islets are found about 16 km (10 miles) off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer sites than last week.
The red tide has also been observed in Pasco County.
Moderate concentrations in or off Pinellas County were reported last week, low to high concentrations off Hillsborough County, higher concentrations in Manatee County, higher concentrations at the bottom of Sarasota County or offshore, high average concentrations in Charlotte County and low concentrations at the bottom of Lee County and offshore.
Respiratory irritation persists in the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
No respiratory irritation has been reported in northwestern Florida over the past week.
